    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf-help-tooltip-term",
      "value": "Conversion taxes on a Roth IRA"
    }
  },
  {
    "verifyText": {
      "id": "lf-help-tooltip-text",
      "value": "If you decide to convert your regular IRA to a Roth IRA, you will have to pay income taxes on the money that you have already contributed. This is because your contributions to the regular IRA were tax-deductible (unless you earn too much, in which case your contributions are taxed) and contributions to a Roth IRA are made after you pay income taxes. The IRS generally requires you to complete a Roth conversion within 60 days. The Roth conversion analyzer lets you pay taxes from one of five options: 1) cash, accounting for any tax savings from the Roth conversion; 2) cash, ignoring any tax savings from the Roth conversion; 3) borrowings; 4) an early withdrawal from the regular IRA and paying the 10% penalty; or 5) a withdrawal from a regular IRA that does not require paying the penalty."
    }
  },
